<script>componentRenderQueue.push(function() {ReactDOM.render(React.createElement(Components.Reading, {"Html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eIt has been a febrile and turbulent month for Russian\u0026ndash;Western relations. While immediate tensions have eased, recent developments offer lessons that reflect, and will influence, a deteriorating relationship.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eA wide range of contentious issues has been on display. First, Russia\u0026rsquo;s biggest military build-up since 2014 highlighted its capacity to mobilise significant force on Europe\u0026rsquo;s border. This stoked deep concern, and a flurry of diplomacy, in the European Union and NATO.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eSecond, revelations that Russian intelligence officers were responsible for a fatal explosion at a Czech arms depot in 2014 drew renewed attention to Russian espionage and subversion. The fact that two of the operatives had later carried out the 2018 Salisbury nerve agent attack amplified concerns. In response, several EU member states have expelled Russian intelligence officers.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eThird, the human-rights situation in Russia became bleaker. Imprisoned opposition leader Alexei Navalny, whose welfare Western leaders have raised with President Vladimir Putin, went on hunger strike. He ended it 24 days later when close to death. The authorities have dismantled the Anti-Corruption Foundation he built up over the previous decade by declaring it an \u0026lsquo;extremist\u0026rsquo; organisation.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eFourth, Russia\u0026rsquo;s internal security organisation, the FSB, claimed to have averted a Western-supported attempt on Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko\u0026rsquo;s life (though, bizarrely, this \u0026lsquo;coloured revolution\u0026rsquo; was supposedly planned by unnamed \u0026lsquo;opposition-minded generals\u0026rsquo;).\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eRelations are now at their most tense and mistrustful for four decades. Russia and the US have recalled their respective ambassadors \u0026ndash; the US after strong Russian pressure to do so. Yet despite these difficulties, President Joe Biden invited his Russian counterpart to a bilateral summit. Putin also took part in Biden\u0026rsquo;s climate summit on 22 April, at the height of concerns about Russia\u0026rsquo;s military build-up.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cspan\u003eUnwelcome display of Western unity\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eThree lessons can be drawn from this intense period. First, Putin lost more than he gained from the military build-up. Although Russia has gained practice in mobilisation, and could yet enhance its position by keeping equipment in place, it has suffered a diplomatic setback. Overall, the West has responded to this test of its resolve by demonstrating strength rather than weakness and division. This first near-crisis is a formative experience for the Biden administration. While few had expected a \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\u0022https://www.iiss.org/blogs/analysis/2020/10/russeurasia---biden-and-russia\u0022\u003e\u003cspan\u003ebetter relationship\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan\u003e with Russia, any case for pursuing it appears weaker than ever. And though some \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\u0022https://cepa.org/putins-game-what-just-happened/\u0022\u003e\u003cspan\u003eargue\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan\u003e that Russia\u0026rsquo;s build-up exposed Ukraine\u0026rsquo;s vulnerability (despite President Volodymyr Zelensky\u0026rsquo;s defiant stand), the other side of this coin is that the US is sensitised to the threat and will plan accordingly.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eEurope, too, stiffened its resolve despite a campaig