 imagery and other technologies make it easier than ever to track force movements (though Russia made no efforts to conceal its build-up), assessing intent remains difficult. Opinions are divided on whether Russia was merely sabre-rattling or planned to escalate its intervention in Ukraine. But this is a false distinction. A large (not merely token) force that demonstrates strength can also use it. Sabres that are rattled may be drawn. Force deployment can serve many possible purposes simultaneously, with the choices between them shifting with political opportunity and circumstance.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eThere are hints that Russia may have kept open the possibility of escalating force until a late stage of its build-up. Putin\u0026rsquo;s annual address to parliament on 21 April was trailed as \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\u0022https://openmedia.io/news/n3/razgovor-o-poslanii-s-ego-avtorom-vneurochnoe-pyatnichnoe-zasedanii-soveta-federacii-mozhet-posetit-prezident/\u0022\u003e\u003cspan\u003ehighly significant\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan\u003e. \u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\u0022color: #222222;\u0022\u003eTwo days before he gave it, Putin convened a meeting to discuss its contents. Such a late meeting has happened only once before \u0026ndash; in 2020, before Putin announced major constitutional changes and a new government. Three days before that, on 16 April, a Security Council \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\u0022http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/page/3\u0022\u003e\u003cspan\u003emeeting\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\u0022color: #222222;\u0022\u003e discussed military issues, with Chief of the General Staff Valery Gerasimov giving the main report \u0026ndash; the first time this had happened since December 2020.\u0026nbsp; Before Putin\u0026rsquo;s address, Federation Council Speaker Valentina Matviyenko \u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\u0022https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4761186#id